T1  - Determinants of Aspiration Levels in a Simulated Goal Setting Environment of the Firm
AU  - Wilsted, William D.
AU  - Hand, Herbert H.
Y1  - 1974/03/01
PY  - 1974
DA  - 1974/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/254783
DO  - 10.5465/254783
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 172
EP  - 177
VL  - 17
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article presents research which examined the theory of aspiration levels in a simulated goal setting environment of a firm. The study included four tasks which were selected to test the primary hypothesis which include return on investment, market share, product market opportunities and number of plants. A management simulation game was used to simulate the complexity of the task and environment of goal setting in the firm. The statistical results of the study support the hypothesis that previous goals, previous performance, and competitor's previous performance form an effective predictor of aspiration levels in a subsequent time period.
AB  - The article presents research which examined the theory of aspiration levels in a simulated goal setting environment of a firm. The study included four tasks which were selected to test the primary hypothesis which include return on investment, market share, product market opportunities and number of plants. A management simulation game was used to simulate the complexity of the task and environment of goal setting in the firm. The statistical results of the study support the hypothesis that previous goals, previous performance, and competitor's previous performance form an effective predictor of aspiration levels in a subsequent time period.
