DO  - 10.5465/254781
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 160
EP  - 167
VL  - 17
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article provides information on a study by J. A. Alutto and J. A. Belasco, which examined the effectiveness of participation decision making. A small western New York cutting tool manufacturing firm was used in the study. The questionnaire was comprised of a series of scales and sets of questions concerning both organizational and individual characteristics. The authors found that the distribution of subjects among decisional conditions in their research was quite different from that observed in the Alutto and Belasco research. The authors of this study also found that contrary to the findings of Alutto and Belasco's research, interpersonal trust was related to the amount of decisional deprivation, while age and seniority was not.
AB  - The article provides information on a study by J. A. Alutto and J. A. Belasco, which examined the effectiveness of participation decision making. A small western New York cutting tool manufacturing firm was used in the study. The questionnaire was comprised of a series of scales and sets of questions concerning both organizational and individual characteristics. The authors found that the distribution of subjects among decisional conditions in their research was quite different from that observed in the Alutto and Belasco research. The authors of this study also found that contrary to the findings of Alutto and Belasco's research, interpersonal trust was related to the amount of decisional deprivation, while age and seniority was not.
